Airbnb Market Analysis - Part II¶

The idea of this notebook is to give you some insights of airbnb San Francisco market as well as the factors that can affect a host's revenue. Part II will mainly focus on the occupancy part.

monthly income of a host = price * monthly occupancy

About occupancy label¶

Currently there are no publicly available and verifiable sources to precisely identify the occupancy rate of Airbnb units. However, there are several indicators combined together can give a reasonable estimate of the occupancy.

  • calendar. The next 30 days of booking calendar on each listing is an approximation of the next 30 days occupancy. However, when a day is blocked for booking, the calendar data does not provide any information whether it is booked by a guest or blocked by the host.

  • reviews rate. Airbnb guests may leave a review after their stay, and these can be used as an indicator of airbnb activity. According to Inside Airbnb, the overall review rate is around 50% for the number of guests making a booking who leave a review.

  • Average length of stay per guest is 4.2 days, according to "Overview of the Airbnb Community in San Francisco" by airbnb.

I used available_30 column as my target, which means the total number of days available for booking for the next 30 days at that scraping day. To make sure it is real guest booking calendar (not host blocking), I need such listing to prove itself that it had received "enough" reviews in the last 30 days, given its actual booking situation. In other words, a hot listing today, is supposed to have a lot of reviews last month. But how many is enough? There is no principled way to define it, here is what I did:

The number of reviews left in the past 30 days should be greater or equal to the anticipated number of guests that could leave reviews in the next 30 days if the calendar information is 'real'. This is a conservative estimate, since with time passing by, the real booked days could be higher than the total number of available days at that scraped day.

Sudo code:

  • If number of reviews in the last month >= (30 - available_30) / 4.2 days (average stay) * 0.5 (reviews rate) is True => kept in my training set; removed such listing if otherwise.

  • If (30 - available_30) / 4.2 * 0.5 < 1, i.e. available_30 > 21 => look into last 2 month => number of reviews in the last 2 month >= (30 - available_30) / 4.2 * 0.5 => True to keep, False to remove.

  • If (30 - available_30) / 4.2 * 0.5 < 0.5, i.e. available_30 > 25 => look into last 3 month; so on and so forth.
  • If available_30 == 30 => we don't need any past reviews, because the host did not block any day, every day is available for booking.

Here is the data after going through all the process above:

  • Outer Richmond
  • Downtown/Civic Center
  • Outer Sunset
  • Inner Sunset
  • Seacliff

Relatively low occupancy neighbourhoods are

  • Crocker Amazon
  • Chinatown
  • Treasure island
  • Golden Gate Park

According Airbnb, Instant Bookable Listings don't require approval from the host before they can be booked. If a host controls more listings, (those listings are more like a hotel for me), the instant bookable proportion tends to be higher for those cases. But operating like a hotel or using a service company does not necessarily lead to higher review score or income per bedroom.

Let's look at how the top hosts describe their houses by the key-words.

In [214]:
top1000listings = listings.sort_values(by=['occupancy_30','income per bedroom month'], ascending=False).head(1000)
In [209]:
tokenizer = RegexpTokenizer(r"[\w']+")
stop_set = set(stopwords.words('english') + ['room', 'bedroom','San','Francisco', 'apartment', 'Guest','guest'])
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer() 
def tokenize(text):
    tokens = tokenizer.tokenize(text)
    lemm = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(token) for token in tokens if token not in stop_set]
    return lemm
